Flow+%28psychology%29&amp;rft.aufirst=J.&amp;rft.aulast=Chen&amp;rft.btitle=Flow+in+Games&amp;rft.date=2008&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.jenovachen.com%2Fflowingames%2Fintroduction.htm&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-JSint-54"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-JSint_54-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web">Miller, Ross (2006-09-18). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.joystiq.com/2006/09/18/joystiq-qanda-jenova-chen/">"Joystiq interview: Jenova Chen"</a>. <a href="/wiki/Joystiq" title="Joystiq">Joystiq</a>. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20090102012220/http://www.joystiq.com/2006/09/18/joystiq-qanda-jenova-chen/">Archived</a> from the original on 2009-01-02<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">2011-01-05</span></span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFlow+%28psychology%29&amp;rft.aufirst=Ross&amp;rft.aulast=Miller&amp;rft.btitle=Joystiq+interview%3A+Jenova+Chen&amp;rft.date=2006-09-18&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.pub=Joystiq&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.joystiq.com%2F2006%2F09%2F18%2Fjoystiq-qanda-jenova-chen%2F&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-55"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-55">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Hans Van der Heijden (2004) User Acceptance of Hedonic Information Systems, MIS Quarterly, vol. 28(4), pp. 695-704</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-56"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-56">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFMichael_Lopp2007" class="citation"><a href="/wiki/Rands" title="Rands">Michael Lopp</a> (12 June 2007), <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.randsinrepose.com/archives/2006/07/10/a_nerd_in_a_cave.html">"Chapter 25: A Nerd in a Cave"</a>, <i>Managing Humans: Biting and Humorous Tales of a Software Engineering Manager</i>, <a href="/wiki/Apress" title="Apress">Apress</a>, p.&#160;143, <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-59059-844-3" title="Special:BookSources/978-1-59059-844-3">978-1-59059-844-3</a>, <q>[The Zone] is a deeply creative space where inspiration is built. Anything which you perceive as beautiful, useful, or fun comes from someone stumbling through The Zone.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFlow+%28psychology%29&amp;rft.atitle=Chapter+25%3A+A+Nerd+in+a+Cave&amp;rft.au=Michael+Lopp&amp;rft.btitle=Managing+Humans%3A+Biting+and+Humorous+Tales+of+a+Software+Engineering+Manager&amp;rft.date=2007-06-12&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-59059-844-3&amp;rft.pages=143&amp;rft.pub=Apress&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.randsinrepose.com%2Farchives%2F2006%2F07%2F10%2Fa_nerd_in_a_cave.html&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-57"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-57">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFJoel_Spolsky2000" class="citation"><a href="/wiki/Joel_Spolsky" title="Joel Spolsky">Joel Spolsky</a> (9 August 2000), <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.joelonsoftware.com/articles/fog0000000043.html"><i>The Joel Test: 12 Steps to Better Code</i></a>, <q>We all know that knowledge workers work best by getting into \'flow\', also known as being \'in the zone\' (...) Writers, programmers, scientists, and even basketball players will tell you about being in the zone.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFlow+%28psychology%29&amp;rft.au=Joel+Spolsky&amp;rft.btitle=The+Joel+Test%3A+12+Steps+to+Better+Code&amp;rft.date=2000-08-09&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.joelonsoftware.com%2Farticles%2Ffog0000000043.html&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-58"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-58">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://catb.org/jargon/html/H/hack-mode.html">"Hack Mode"</a>. <a href="/wiki/Jargon_File" title="Jargon File">Jargon File</a>. 12 November 2013.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFlow+%28psychology%29&amp;rft.btitle=Hack+Mode&amp;rft.date=2013-11-12&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.pub=Jargon+File&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fcatb.org%2Fjargon%2Fhtml%2FH%2Fhack-mode.html&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-59"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-59">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFScott_Rosenberg2007" class="citation"><a href="/wiki/Scott_Rosenberg_(journalist)" title="Scott Rosenberg (journalist)">Scott Rosenberg</a> (2007), <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.dreamingincode.com/book-excerpt/"><i>Dreaming in Code: Two Dozen Programmers, Three Years, 4,732 Bugs, and One Quest for Transcendent Software</i></a>, <q>When things go well, you can lose track of passing hours in the state psychologists call "flow." When things go badly, you get stuck, frozen between dimensions, unable to move or see a way forward. Either way, you\'ve left the clock far behind. You\'re on software time.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFlow+%28psychology%29&amp;rft.au=Scott+Rosenberg&amp;rft.btitle=Dreaming+in+Code%3A+Two+Dozen+Programmers%2C+Three+Years%2C+4%2C732+Bugs%2C+and+One+Quest+for+Transcendent+Software&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.dreamingincode.com%2Fbook-excerpt%2F&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-Visser_2007-60"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Visser_2007_60-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Visser_2007_60-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web">Visser, Coert. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://articlescoertvisser.blogspot.com/2007/11/good-business-leadership-flow-and.html">"Good Business: Leadership, Flow, and the Making of Meaning"</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">26 September</span> 2012</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFlow+%28psychology%29&amp;rft.aufirst=Coert&amp;rft.aulast=Visser&amp;rft.btitle=Good+Business%3A+Leadership%2C+Flow%2C+and+the+Making+of+Meaning&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Farticlescoertvisser.blogspot.com%2F2007%2F11%2Fgood-business-leadership-flow-and.html&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-61"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-61">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation journal">Foster, Sandra; Lloyd, Paul (2007). "Positive Psychology Principles Applied to Consulting Psychology at the Individual and Group Level". <i>Consulting Psychology Journal: Practice and Research</i>. <b>59</b> (1): 30\xe2\x80\x9340.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFlow+%28psychology%29&amp;rft.atitle=Positive+Psychology+Princip